👉 In Kubernetes, the system is divided into:

Control Plane (Brain) 🧠
Worker Nodes (Hands) 🖥️
🚀 In Amazon EKS

👉 AWS manages the Control Plane for you

🧠 Control Plane = Brain of Kubernetes

It is responsible for:

Deciding where containers should run
Managing cluster state
Handling API requests
🔍 Components inside Control Plane

You don’t see them directly, but they exist:

🧩 1. API Server

👉 Entry point for everything

kubectl talks to this
Receives commands

Example:

kubectl get nodes
🧩 2. Scheduler

👉 Decides:

Which node should run a pod
🧩 3. Controller Manager

👉 Ensures:

Desired state = Actual state

Example:

If pod crashes → recreate automatically
🧩 4. etcd (Database)

👉 Stores:

Cluster data
Configurations
Current state
🧠 What happens when you create cluster

When you run:

eksctl create cluster

👉 AWS:

Creates Control Plane (managed by EKS)
Makes it highly available (multi-AZ)
Secures it
Exposes API endpoint
🔥 Important point

👉 You DON’T manage control plane in EKS

AWS handles:

Updates
Scaling
Security
Availability
🧩 Worker Nodes vs Control Plane
Component	Role
Control Plane	Brain (decisions)
Worker Nodes	Execute containers
🧠 Real-time example

You run:

kubectl create deployment nginx

👉 Flow:

Request → API Server
Scheduler → picks node
Node runs container
Controller ensures it stays running
💡 Interview answer

👉 “What is EKS control plane?”

You can say:

“The control plane in EKS is the managed Kubernetes brain that handles API requests, scheduling, cluster state, and automation, and is fully managed by AWS.”

🎯 Simple memory

👉 Control Plane = Thinks
👉 Nodes = Works

✔️ Final clarity
You created cluster → Control Plane created
Then node group → Worker nodes created

👉 Both together = working Kubernetes cluster

